Emergency Medical Services paramedics gathered outside the Khayelitsha Magistrate&#8217;s Court on Friday in protest against attacks on emergency personnel as three suspects appeared in court.Two 19-year-old&#8217;s were arrested for robbing paramedics in December and their accomplice, a 24-year-old man, was arrested for being in possession of stolen items.The EMS paramedics were robbed of their cellphones while they were treating a patient in Mandela Park in Harare, Khayelitsha.The Western Cape Health Department has urged communities and police to work with them to reduce attacks on emergency services workers and facilities. Crime happens to anyone, it can not be stopped, what we are doing as the department of health in the Western Cape we are working with police to make sure that emergency crews are protected when they go to different areas. We also urge community members to work with us and report perpetrators to the police, Western Cape Health spokesperson Luyanda Mfeka said.At least 90 cases of attacks were recorded in 2016 by the department of health in the Western Cape with cases of robberies and intimidation.Two EMS members are currently receiving trauma counselling after the ambulance they were travelling in was stoned in Nyanga.-TNA Reporter 